## Pinia State Management

### Store Structure

Use the **Setup Store** syntax (Composition API style) — not the Options Store.

```typescript
// app/stores/useUserStore.ts
import { defineStore } from 'pinia'
import type { User } from '~/types/user'

export const useUserStore = defineStore('users', () => {
  // State
  const users = ref<User[]>([])
  const selectedUser = ref<User | null>(null)
  const loading = ref(false)

  // Getters
  const activeUsers = computed(() =>
    users.value.filter((u) => !u.deletedAt)
  )

  // Actions
  async function fetchAll() {
    loading.value = true
    try {
      users.value = await $fetch('/api/users')
    } finally {
      loading.value = false
    }
  }

  async function createUser(data: { name: string; email: string }) {
    const created = await $fetch('/api/users', { method: 'POST', body: data })
    users.value.push(created)
    return created
  }

  return { users, selectedUser, loading, activeUsers, fetchAll, createUser }
})
```

### When to Use a Store

| Use a store | Use a composable |
|---|---|
| Data shared across multiple pages | Data local to one component or route |
| Global UI state (auth, notifications) | One-off async calls |
| Cached server data used in many places | Component-level loading/error state |

